skeletal crystal of magnetite, replaced by hematite. the crystal is elongated along the axis of symmetry of the fourth order so that the faces of the rhombic dodecahedron form a tetragonal pseudoprism (with longitudinal slit-like depressions in the center of the faces) completed by a pseudopyramid (octahedron). along one of the edges of this pseudoprism, along the other, "rays" of a skeletal crystal depart from the fourth-order axes, giving the sample a resemblance to a ship. these "rays" have the same cut as the main "ray" of the crystal. an additional shine to the crystal is given by small lamellar growths of hematite, oriented mainly parallel to the faces of the octahedron.
